144
15:45.630 --> 15:52.920
There's one other point about query gates that's worth mentioning before we move on, and that is that when we're designing and analyzing query algorithms,

145
15:52.920 --> 15:57.930
we don't worry at all about how
query gates are implemented.

146
15:57.930 --> 16:04.650
It's assumed that these
query gates are given to us, and the difficulty of building
them isn't our concern.

147
16:04.650 --> 16:12.690
You can think of the
query gates themselves as being the input if you like, and it's not our job to create the input, we're just trying to
solve a particular problem

148
16:12.690 --> 16:20.280
given the input. Of course, when f is a function
from one bit to one bit, there are only four possible choices,

149
16:20.280 --> 16:27.210
and it would be easy enough
to implement any one of them, but in general, for functions
with many input bits,

150
16:27.210 --> 16:32.520
it could be extremely difficult to implement query gates
for those functions.

151
16:32.520 --> 16:39.210
To be clear, this isn't
to say that the issue of how query gates are
implemented isn't important, but rather that it isn't considered

152
16:39.210 --> 16:43.350
to be part of the cost
of a query algorithm.

153
16:43.350 --> 16:50.490
This is consistent with the idea that this isn't really
about practical computing or actually building circuits per se,

154
16:50.490 --> 16:57.570
it's about working within
a theoretical framework that tells us interesting
things about computation.

155
16:57.570 --> 17:05.370
We will have more to say about this when we make the jump from this model to a more standard model of computation, and that's mainly what the next lesson,

156
17:05.370 --> 17:11.430
Lesson 6, will be about.

157
17:11.430 --> 17:15.030
Now let's turn our attention
to quantum circuits.

158
17:15.030 --> 17:21.060
For quantum circuits, we're going to change the
definition of query gates to make them unitary.

159
17:21.060 --> 17:27.630
We want to be able to make
queries within quantum circuits and for them to operate
linearly on quantum states

160
17:27.630 --> 17:32.550
so that we can effectively
make queries in super position.

161
17:32.550 --> 17:40.230
It might seem like we're moving
the goalposts, so to speak, by changing what we mean by a query in comparison to what we just
saw for Boolean circuits,

162
17:40.230 --> 17:44.850
but there is justification for it that we'll discuss in more
detail in the next lesson.

163
17:44.850 --> 17:48.930
For now, it's just a definition.

164
17:48.930 --> 17:56.280
Specifically, the
definition is as follows, given any function f of
the same form as before,

165
17:56.280 --> 18:03.990
meaning that it maps n bits
strings to m bits strings, the query gate Uf acts on n + m qubits

166
18:03.990 --> 18:09.570
and is defined by the
action described here on standard basis states.

167
18:09.570 --> 18:16.500
We'll see a figure
representing this definition in just a moment, but first, let me make clear the notation
that's being used here,

168
18:16.500 --> 18:23.070
and that is whenever we
use the symbol for the XOR as an operation between two
strings of the same length,

169
18:23.070 --> 18:30.360
we're referring to the
bitwise eXclusive OR, and here you can see an example.

170
18:30.360 --> 18:39.570
In the definition, we have that both y and f of
x are strings of length m, so this string right here
represents the string we get

171
18:39.570 --> 18:48.420
by XORing those two strings
together, one bit at a time, and here's the diagram
explaining how these gates work.

172
18:48.420 --> 18:52.530
The top n qubits correspond to
the argument of the function.

173
18:52.530 --> 19:00.660
And when they start out
in a standard basis state, cat x in this diagram, that standard basis state
goes through unchanged

174
19:00.660 --> 19:03.960
and gets echoed as part of the output.

175
19:03.960 --> 19:10.560
The bottom m qubits correspond to the output
of the function f, and when they start out in
any standard basis state,

176
19:10.560 --> 19:19.560
cat y in this diagram, what happens is that the
output of the function f of x gets XORed onto the string y.

177
19:19.560 --> 19:30.750
This is what happens for
standard basis states, and if we wanna know
what happens in general for other quantum states, we
use linearity, as we always do.

178
19:30.750 --> 19:37.620
A reason to define query gates like this where we echo the input and we use the bitwise XOR for the output

179
19:37.620 --> 19:43.710
is that these gates are always unitary for any choice of the function f.

180
19:43.710 --> 19:46.830
This is, in fact, a
deterministic operation.

181
19:46.830 --> 19:53.160
And if we were to express it as a matrix for any choice of a function F, we'd get a permutation matrix,

182
19:53.160 --> 19:59.340
meaning one with a single one in each row and in each column, and all other entries equal to 0.

183
19:59.340 --> 20:03.780
And permutation matrices
are always unitary.

184
20:03.780 --> 20:14.160
In fact, for this operation, we'll get that the operation
is its own inverse, so Uf dager equals Uf.

185
20:14.160 --> 20:20.160
If all we wanna do with these
gates is to evaluate f of x for some string x, that's easy,

186
20:20.160 --> 20:28.680
we can just set y to
be the all-zero string. So when we take the bit y's eXclusive OR, we end up with just f of x.

187
20:28.680 --> 20:34.200
Here, by the way, you can see the notation that's used to denote the all-zero string.

188
20:34.200 --> 20:37.800
It looks like 0 to the power M, but that's not what it means.

189
20:37.800 --> 20:42.150
It means the string of zeros
having length equal to M.

190
20:42.150 --> 20:50.250
When we're talking about
strings as opposed to numbers, exponents typically mean that we repeat that string
some number of times,

191
20:50.250 --> 20:54.330
so this is 0 repeated m times.

